[{"id":"VH908566","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents 2 diagrams. The first diagram is labeled Diagram 1, and contains a small shaded circle labeled, K with a positive one charge, and a larger unshaded circle labeled, C l with a negative one charge. Water molecules surround the two circles with O atoms facing the K with a positive one charge circle and H atoms facing the C l with a negative one charge circle. The second diagram is labeled Diagram 2 and contains a small shaded circle labeled, K with a delta plus charge, connected to a larger unshaded circle labeled, C l with a delta minus charge. Water molecules surround the molecule with H atoms facing the K with the delta plus charge circle and O atoms facing the C l with a delta minus charge circle.\" height=\"196\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH908566.g01.png\" width=\"650\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the diagrams above best represents the interactions that are responsible for the relatively large solubility of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K C l\"><math alttext=\"K C l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>KCl</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> crystals in water, and why?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH908566_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Diagram 1, because strong ion-dipole interactions between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K C l\"><math alttext=\"K C l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>KCl</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and water help to dissociate the solute.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Diagram 1, because strong London dispersion forces between the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K with a positive one charge\"><math alttext=\"K with a positive one charge\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msup><mrow><mtext>K</mtext></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C l with a negative one charge\"><math alttext=\"C l with a negative one charge\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msup><mrow><mtext>Cl</mtext></mrow><mrow><mo>âˆ’</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ions and water replace the weak London dispersion forces between two water molecules.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Diagram 2, because strong dipole-dipole forces between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K C l\"><math alttext=\"K C l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>KCl</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and water help to separate the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K C l\"><math alttext=\"K C l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>KCl</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> units within the crystals.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Diagram 2, because the hydrogen bonds between water molecules expand to accommodate the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K C l\"><math alttext=\"K C l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>KCl</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> particles and pull them into solution.</p>"],"answer":0}]